      "narrative": {
        "News": "Marathon - Galveston Bay: activity at the 145,000 bpd FCC re- turned to normal operational levels during the evening of July 6 (EST). Decreased activity began at the unit during the afternoon of July 2 (EST). Localized unit cooling began at that time. Lazarus Energy - Nixon: the 15,000 bpd CDU was shut during the afternoon of July 6 (EST). Delek - Big Spring: brief elevated flaring began during the after- noon of July 5 (EST). Similar flaring has previously been associat- ed with operational issues and maintenance. Activity at all moni- tored units remained unchanged.",
        "Ongoing Events": "TotalEnergies - Port Arthur: the 80,000 bpd FCC, 60,000 bpd coker, 10,000 bpd coker naphtha hydrotreater, 66,000 bpd ULSD hydrotreater, 39,600 bpd catalytic reformer and 45,500 bpd re- former feed hydrotreater were restarted during the morning of June 6. Increased activity began at the 80,000 bpd FCC during the morning of June 27. Increased activity began at the 60,000 bpd coker, 10,000 bpd coker naphtha hydrotreater, 66,000 bpd ULSD hydrotreater, 39,600 bpd catalytic reformer and 45,500 bpd re- former feed hydrotreater June 25. The 80,000 bpd CDU and 52,000 bpd VDU were restarted June 30. Also, increased activity halted at the 165,000 bpd CDU and 55,000 bpd VDU June 28 after beginning June 25. All monitored units were shut during the late evening of June 19. GCC Bunkers - Galveston: the 50,000 bpd CDU was restarted during the morning of July 2. The unit was observed to be offline as of the afternoon of June 25. The exact timing of the shutdown is unknown due to a temporary camera outage. Citgo - Corpus Christi: the 44,000 bpd coker was restarted dur- ing the morning of June 20. Increased activity began at the unit during the evening of June 17. The unit was shut on June 14. The 174,000 bpd CDU and 85,300 bpd VDU were shut during the late morning of June 18 and remained offline. The units were ini- tially shut on June 10. PBF - Chalmette: the 19,000 bpd catalytic reformer was shut dur- ing the afternoon of May 8. A fire was reported at the facility. Phillips 66 - Sweeny: the 30,000 bpd FCC was shut during the af- ternoon of March 28. Decreased furnace stack activity began at that time.",
